        • [ - ] lolzzzzzzzz - member since 21-Sep-14

          This is why football stats still have a long way to go. Messi certainly didn't have a truly bad match (somewhere around 7-7.5 to me) but to give him 9 is pretty ridiculous. It's not just the emphasis on dribbles, it's the fact that not every dribble means the same in a match. A dribble out of the defensive side, where the opposing forward is just rushing towards you trying to keep pressure should not weigh the same as a dribble that led to an opening that eventually led to a through pass that created a chance/scored a goal. Now Idk what the weights are for the ratings but I'm not sure it's completely reflecting this matter. Possession as well, having a lot of it is great, but if the opponent is letting you have it, it doesn't really mean a lot. Same for passing accuracy and even aerials with/without pressure.

          5 years ago

        • [ - ] lolzzzzzzzz - member since 21-Sep-14

          @lolzzzzzzzz Just to expand on the issue a bit further, shots on target when 1-on-1 if not converted should not actually increase your rating unless it was total merit of the keeper. Keeping possession without a pressing opponent should not increase rating. Simple passes (sides, backs) should not increase rating unless it was out of a sticky situation (judgment call yes) or effectively led to a chance/goal. A 25-pass move leading to a goal is worth the same as a 5-pass move that leads to the same. Disclaimer is that Idk the formula here but it certainly helps explain some of the ratings oddities seen around, but then again no formula would be perfect.

          5 years ago
